{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 04:00:51.510878", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nExecutive summary\n- Overall routing and reachability across the enterprise fabric are healthy. OSPF adjacencies are up, routes are present end-to-end, and hosts can resolve and reach published services in 10.200.0.0/24.\n- Backend servers are correctly isolated on 20.200.0.0/24 and are not reachable from user subnets, consistent with the design intent that they not be directly accessible.\n- Notable configuration issues were identified on the load balancer (NGINX upstream targets include non-existent backends) and on the “Apache” web servers (HTTP HEAD returns 501), which are application-layer and may impact perceived behavior but are not routing faults.\n\nWhat was tested\n- Broad ICMP reachability across many hosts (lab reachability sweep): 0% loss; RTTs generally low with some minor variance.\n- Host network/DNS config: Both sample hosts (10.1.1.20 and 10.2.1.13) have default gateways and resolv.conf pointing to 10.200.0.2.\n- Pings from hosts to DNS (10.200.0.2), load balancer (10.200.0.7), and web servers (10.200.0.3–10.200.0.6): all successful.\n- HTTP timing tests from hosts:\n  - http://web0.local: TTFB ~0.2–1.3s; total ~1.0–2.1s (variable but successful).\n  - http://web99.local (NGINX LB): TTFB ~0.2–0.4s; total ~1.0–1.23s across runs (consistent success).\n- DNS resolution with getent: web0.local -> 10.200.0.3; web1/2/3.local -> 10.200.0.4/.5/.6; web99.local -> 10.200.0.7 (OK).\n- OSPF state and routing (FRR on all routers): all neighbors Full; 10.200.0.0/24 is advertised by server_access_router; user subnets are learned as expected; no flaps seen.\n- Backend network isolation:\n  - From hosts: ping 20.200.0.2 -> “Destination Net Unreachable” from local gateway (no route), confirming isolation and non-advertisement of 20.200.0.0/24.\n  - On the LB: eth1 20.200.0.1/24; backend_web_0 is 20.200.0.2/24; LB can ping backend (OK).\n\nFindings and anomalies\n1) Core/Distribution/Server OSPF health: NORMAL\n- All OSPF adjacencies Full. Server farm (10.200.0.0/24) is present in cores and dists.\n- Inter-area routes and next hops look correct; no missing routes observed for published services.\n\n2) End-to-end host connectivity to services: NORMAL\n- Hosts in representative subnets can resolve and ping DNS and web services and reach LB VIP via DNS names.\n- Curl timing shows successful transactions with low TTFB; no evidence of network-induced failures.\n\n3) Backend server isolation: NORMAL (by design)\n- 20.200.0.0/24 is not present in OSPF; hosts’ gateways send ICMP Net Unreachable to 20.200.0.2, so backends are not directly accessible from user subnets.\n- LB can reach 20.200.0.2 via its backend interface eth1.\n\n4) Load balancer upstream configuration: ABNORMAL (configuration risk)\n- NGINX config on load_balancer defines upstream “web99” with:\n  - server 20.200.0.2:80; server 20.200.0.3:80; server 20.200.0.4:80\n- Only one backend is actually present/connected (backend_web_0 at 20.200.0.2). There is no evidence of 20.200.0.3 or 20.200.0.4 hosts in the topology or ARP/OS.\n- Impact: NGINX may attempt to balance to non-existent upstreams (depending on failure handling), potentially causing intermittent retries/delays if not marked down. Current curl timing did not show timeouts, but this remains a misconfiguration and a potential cause of intermittent performance issues.\n\n5) Web servers’ HTTP behavior vs. stated design: POTENTIAL MISMATCH (application-level)\n- HTTP HEAD to web1/2/3.local (10.200.0.4/.5/.6) returns “HTTP/1.0 501 Unsupported method (‘HEAD’)” on both sample hosts.\n- Stated design calls these “Apache web servers,” which normally handle HEAD. This suggests they may be running a different HTTP daemon or be misconfigured. Network path is fine; issue is at application layer.\n\n6) Minor observations\n- Some ICMP RTT variance (occasionally up to ~12 ms) across various host pairs; zero packet loss. Likely testbed load, not path issues.\n- DHCP appears functional (hosts got dynamic IPs and default routes); not deeply tested beyond that.\n\nLocalization and root cause\n- NGINX load balancer configuration (device: load_balancer):\n  - Root cause: Upstream list references two non-existent backend endpoints (20.200.0.3 and 20.200.0.4). This is a config inconsistency that can degrade load-balancing behavior.\n- Web servers (devices: web_server_1, web_server_2, web_server_3):\n  - Root cause: HTTP service returns 501 to HEAD, inconsistent with expected Apache behavior. This is an application/server configuration issue, not a network fault.\n- Routing/OSPF fabric (devices: core and distribution routers, server_access_router):\n  - No anomalies; routing and adjacencies healthy.\n- Backend isolation (policy):\n  - Working as intended; 20.200.0.0/24 not advertised, unreachable from user subnets, reachable from LB.\n\nConclusion\n- Network fabric health: Good.\n- Service reachability: Good for DNS, public web VIPs, and direct web servers.\n- Identified issues are configuration-level on the load balancer (non-existent upstreams in NGINX config) and application behavior on the “Apache” servers (HEAD 501). No corrective actions are proposed here per scope.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 47593, "output_tokens": 4323, "total_tokens": 51916, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 45184}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2944}}}
